          "body": "Verse 8 is one of the most important single verses in the chapter because it shows the precise mechanism of obedience: 'when Asa heard these words and the prophecy which Azariah son of Oded the prophet spoke, he took courage.' The word (*chazaq*) is the same verb God used in the command of verse 7. God commanded courage; Asa enacted it. And courage immediately produced action: he removed the abominable idols, he extended the purge into captured northern cities, and he restored the altar of the LORD before the porch of the temple. The sequence — word heard → courage taken → specific obedience enacted — is the Chronicler's template for authentic leadership response to prophetic word. The reform is not vague spiritual renewal; it involves specific objects in specific places: detestable idols removed, a particular altar restored, a specific territory purged. Reform that stops short of specific action is not yet reform."
