        "range": "15:8",
        "excerpt": "He took courage and removed the abominable idols from all the land of Judah and Benjamin and from the cities which he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim. He then restored the altar of the LORD which was in front of the porch of the LORD.",
        "body": "Verse 8 is the hinge of the chapter — the point at which prophetic word becomes royal action. The Chronicler is precise about the mechanics: Asa *heard* the words and prophecy, he *took courage* (*chazaq* — the same verb God commanded in v.7), and *then* he acted. There is no gap between the courage and the obedience. This is the Chronicler's model of authentic prophetic reception: the word produces courage, and courage immediately produces specific, irreversible action.\n\nThe reform has two movements: destruction and restoration. First, Asa removed the 'abominable idols' (*shiqqutsim*) — the term is one of the Bible's strongest expressions of divine revulsion toward cult objects. The Chronicler is deliberately adopting God's evaluative vocabulary, not neutral archaeological language. Then Asa restored the altar of the LORD 'which was in front of the porch of the LORD.' The altar's state of disrepair implied that sacrificial worship had been neglected; its restoration means that the legal, God-ordained means of approaching God are re-established before the covenant assembly is convened. You cannot covenant with God without first restoring the altar through which He receives worship.\n\nThe geographical breadth of the reform is significant: it extends into 'cities which he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim.' Asa's father Abijah had taken northern cities (13:19), and Asa exercises religious jurisdiction over them. The Chronicler's pan-Israelite vision — that the Davidic king is the legitimate king of all twelve tribes — is active here: reform of Judah is not enough; the captured territories must be purged as well.\n\nChuck Swindoll observed that leaders who reform institutions without first restoring worship have cleaned the outside of the cup. Asa restores the altar — the point of sacrificial access — before gathering the people. The order matters: worship-restoration precedes covenant-renewal.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shiqquts* (abominable idols) is the Deuteronomic term for objects of cultic horror (Deuteronomy 29:17; 1 Kings 11:5, 7). *Chadash* (restored, renewed, 15:8) — to make new, to renew something that had fallen into disuse or decay. The altar was not built; it was *renewed* — a signal that the structure of true worship remained, however neglected."
