        "excerpt": "They entered into the covenant to seek the LORD God of their fathers with all their heart and soul… All Judah rejoiced concerning the oath, for they had sworn with their whole heart and had sought Him earnestly, and He let them find Him.",
        "body": "The assembly of verses 9-15 is one of the great covenant-renewal scenes in Chronicles, and it is distinguished from mere religious performance by two features: it cost something (700 oxen and 7,000 sheep from the spoil, 15:11) and it was sworn with whole heart (15:12, 15). The sacrifice from the spoil signals that the war plunder — won through God's provision — is consecrated back to God rather than consumed privately. This is the logic of the tithe applied to military victory: the first and best returns to the Giver.\n\nThe defection of northerners (15:9) is the chapter's most striking ecclesiological detail. People from Ephraim, Manasseh, and Simeon — tribes of the apostate northern kingdom — cross political and religious lines to join the assembly because 'they saw that the LORD his God was with him.' The visibility of God's presence on a faithful leader is itself an evangelistic force. The Chronicler is making a consistent theological point across the narrative: genuine covenant faithfulness draws a remnant. The northern defectors in Asa's day anticipate the northern participation in Hezekiah's Passover (30:11) and the eschatological gathering of all Israel under the Davidic king.\n\nThe covenant of verse 12 is Deuteronomic in its structure and Shema-like in its language — 'with all their heart and soul' (cf. Deuteronomy 6:5; 10:12; 11:13). The death penalty for non-seekers (15:13) should not be softened. This is theocratic covenant enforcement within the context of a national covenant community — analogous to the Deuteronomic sanctions for apostasy (Deuteronomy 13:6-10; 17:12). The covenanting people are not constructing new law; they are applying existing Mosaic covenant terms to their specific situation.\n\nThe oath scene of verses 14-15 is deliberately sensory: loud voice, shouting, trumpets, and horns. The public, audible, communal character of the commitment matters to the Chronicler because it distinguishes private intention from binding covenant pledge. The result is the chapter's climactic promise fulfilled: 'He let them find Him. So the LORD gave them rest on every side.' The seeking-and-finding of verse 2 — the conditional promise — becomes in verse 15 a reported historical event. Covenant-theology is not speculation; it is history in advance.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Berit* (covenant, 15:12) is the standard Sinaitic covenant term. *Levav* and *nephesh* (heart and soul, 15:12) are the two components of the Shema's love-command (Deuteronomy 6:5). *Nuach* (gave rest, 15:15) is the Sabbath-rest root — the peace given is not merely military but the covenant-shalom that belongs to the age of fulfillment. The Chronicler uses it in the same way as Solomon's rest in 1 Kings 5:4."
